U.S.: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is comical that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself considered the most stupid, on the Afghan issue.
When he finally revealed his long-awaited Afghan approach, it turned out to be a copy of the script Bush used for Iraq, created three years ago.
Not only is the same text repeatedly used in the phrase "just like Iraq", but he also hesitated to use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement for his own statement: "A new road forward".
It was he himself who three years ago criticized Bush's idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from civil war, and criticized it as "an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences".
The following months, however, proved that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful one, so that today there is no mention of Iraq in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, but he objectively left his successor with a much more favorable initial situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama expects the miracle to repeat itself.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander in chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal.
He asked for 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn't think of anything better, so at least he fooled the general about 10,000 military personnel.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself had previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic part of Obama's entire strategy seems to be his goal, starting withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and finishing this process in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is being fulfilled.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, if they are used to changing the head every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated because of the confusing relations, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is "capable of action", a minimum goal of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama's strategy is shattered by his volunteerism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now about to explode.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "come home soon", will perform some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is sheer irresponsibility, as the Taliban will view it as an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that Europeans are less and less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their constituents, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to seek answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the successful withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive thing for Barack Obama is the fact that three years remain until the presidential election and that there is still a lot of time left to find another strategy, if this proves a total failure.
