Czech discovery: an effective substance even in 'crossroads' HIV viruses
Czech and German scientists are testing new compounds that can moderate the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this enhanced substance is that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus as some medicines already available.
AIDS is not curable until now.
However, patients' lives can be significantly extended by a combination of medicines that prevent HIV from replicating in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the drugs no longer work.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Czech Academy of Sciences, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metallic carbohydrates have an effect on albumin, responsible for the spread of HIV.
Metalocarbons are composed of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way that is different from all medicines used today, and so they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists find new, improved compounds, prepared by knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus' albumin.
Metal carbons have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and it's essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, there is no HIV fractionation and no mature and infectious virus bodies would be created.
If we stop HIV proteasis, we will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In an article published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which is still systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective
Testing of the effect of this series of substances on HIV proteases was carried out on probeta, and also against its resistant variants, obtained from HIV patients.
The effect of metallocarbons on the common enzyme variant is not as strong as in clinically used medicines, but they do not lose their effect on resistant variants, in which medicines often do not work.
