In On Thin Ice, Richard Ellis, a writer and illustrator, paints a natural history of the northern icon, the polar bear.
A knowledgeable of the complicated history and politics of whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arctic explorers, who gave proof of courage by confronting the white bear.
Admiral Nelson's encounter as a brave 14-year-old cadet, fighting only with the tip of his musket, is surely a myth, but others are true.
The young, caught swimming after the bodies of their newly exterminated mothers, were caught and sent to zoos and circuses.
