Ellis draws on stories from other writers and historians, and often returns to the threat hunters pose to the survival of species.
Although banned in Norway, the US and Russia, the killing continues in Greenland and Canada, where helicopter hunters and snowmobile Eskimos use high-powered assault rifles to shoot down prey.
Ironically, it's in the waters north of those two hunter nations where the ice will last longer.
In his new book, "After the Ice", Alun Anderson, a former New Scientist editor, offers a clear, chilling account of Arctic science and a startling look at how the future of that place can be transformed.
It's not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheric scientists nor oceanographers can adequately explain the speed of change.
It's not for lack of commitment.
Fridtjof Nansen's pioneering travels in the late 19th and early 20th centuries gave clues for the first time about the displacement of ice masses.
