A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, characterized by so far-reaching defiant stances and mutual recriminations, drew renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that predicts ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying the bulk of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as a major breakthrough in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Drafted by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not mention how much money rich countries would give to the poor to tackle global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for the key questions, including how the developed and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit of the global temperature rise that policy makers would be willing to tolerate.
This gives the process a lot of flexibility, said John Coequyt, senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the top UN climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as "the big picture".
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 by 25 to 45 percent, compared to 1990 levels, while the major developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would cut emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also spurred the talks on Friday, pledging $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, Friday was the same kind of verbal fireworks that dominated the conversation last week.
The US special climate envoy Todd Stern rejected claims that they call for mandatory greenhouse gas emission cuts for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if not financed by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China, compared to what Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not make a deal without the major developing countries moving forward and taking action, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said the top U.S. climate negotiator lacked "common sense", or was "very irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the United States would not help China economically to deal with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, fault lines have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing off over their respective obligations, while poorer nations insist that the world's 24 most influential countries are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it's not surprising that the major powers are discussing who should pay the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even as vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in seeking to contain the big emitters responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is developing, said Ulate, who also works as a regional adviser on climate change in Mexico and Central America, for Conservation International.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to push for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants say the talks will yield at most a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, drafted a 24-page preliminary treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said the push by small island nations has "put political pressure on the entire political process", in part because they are now unified and demanding action from emerging economies such as China and India.
