Management revolution or the end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of French big companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
Over a decade ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the attitude of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees adhering to 'values' determined from above, as before it was about imposing products designed by factory technicians on consumers.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to market-conquest strategies... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that have no relation to customer preference factors is regularly repeated.
A demobilization of employees can lead to a deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much broader phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the enterprise, particularly R & D and even more so business intelligence.
Indeed, Business Intelligence (BI) "requires all parties involved (...) to have proactive conduct and a forward-looking vision"; it needs a commitment on the part of employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
We therefore called for a management revolution, which would involve putting employees at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative usefulness
Will internal opinion polls, such as the Orange survey of employees, incite the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many laps, all companies end up doing essentially what they always did!
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Lastly, because most executives have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Because they come from the great engineering schools, they interpret psychology in a mechanical way.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the old behavioural theory that American "neuroscience" recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Research and the media widely circulated behind their backs.
In this way, suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanical management stance, unsuitable for today's world.
