The Cradle of the Dinosaur
The Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-meter-long, 1.50-meter-high animal that ran on its two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, this wouldn't have been anything special.
But the Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to have these bodily characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at the time was in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangea on the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It tells us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the spread, and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavation in 2006 at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes, we've found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a team member at the Utah Museum of Natural History.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
During the excavation they collected the remains of five specimens.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the Hopi sun god.
Sterling Nesbitt says that "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found".
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, when the saurians were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: carnivorous theropods, including Tyrannosaurus Rex, Velociraptor and also birds, quadruped sauropods known as "long-necked" sauropods and their relatives, and herbivores (bird-bellied sauropods), to which, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus belong.
According to Nesbitt and his colleagues' analysis, Tawa hallae is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, Nesbitt says.
For example, in the skull of Tawa hallae, researchers found evidence of air pockets, such as those also held by the descendants of theropods, birds.
Thanks to air bags, birds breathe more efficiently than mammals.
In the case of Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbag-operated theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the lineage of later giant sauropods also possessed airbags and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the earliest known dinosaurs lived in South America, researchers conclude that the saurians first appeared there.
As a result, the three genealogical lineages were initially separated and spread from South America to all corners of the earth, which at that time still formed a single landmass, the supercontinent Pangaea.
However, the facts say that the team found along with Tawa hallae the remains of two other theropods not closely related.
All three cannot descend from a single, related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that there were at least three migratory waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the study Science.
Of course, there are opponents as well.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a brother group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
Their view could give a distorted picture, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral lineage of reptiles to the dominant land vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains a mystery.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic, dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of the current crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs spread throughout the world and many new species developed, while the kinship became extinct at the Triassic boundary towards the Jurassic.
Success stories were not eternal.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat their opponents in the area.
Success stories aren't always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact slowed the rise of a group of species, which had also already evolved in the Triassic and since then have led a miserable existence: mammals.
