75% of working mothers have had work problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for younger generation women who want to be mothers.
This is revealed in the study 'Fertility and career of women in Spain', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 shows no doubt about this: 75% of working mothers have found employment opportunities limited because of maternity.
The study shows that there are many differences in the start of cohabitation and the number of children, depending on whether or not they work and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have an unstable job start cohabitation earlier, advance their first maternity, and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
"Women between 35 and 49 years old with fixed jobs have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting cohabitation, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time from their life path to get them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work carried out exerts a great influence on motherhood but less on the timing of mating", explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that makes the age difference between women getting married and having their first offspring.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the older the couple gets married and the older their first child is.
The difference also remains between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group of 35-49, those with primary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
"Another division is also established between women based on their level of education.
While those with basic education get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, those of middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a condition prior to marriage and the arrival of a child", Delgado details.
