Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As with the ABS brake block and will pass the ESP stability check, emergency braking support systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all newly registered light commercial and passenger cars, while a shortage period is fixed for the rest until the end of February 2011.
The European Union's measure aims to increase pedestrian protection, although its working method can also help prevent many collisions by reach.
The emergency brake assistant does what it does is increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the driver's pitch.
But this one doesn't always keep that pressure up until the end.
According to a study by car component manufacturer Bosch, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not reached the brake before the collision and half of them had not used all the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The aid intervention, on the other hand, requires the braking system to be kept at its maximum, reducing the distance the car takes to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with these types of devices, up to 1,100 pedestrian-related fatal accidents could be avoided each year.
The reduction will be even greater - one in four accidents involving damage to people is estimated to be avoided - when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems are introduced.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via a radar or a camera) detects obstacles and alerts the driver, as well as acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
In the event that it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device shall apply maximum effort to the brakes to minimize damage.
